It was goof because it understood that and embraced that and was a excellent movie because it wasn't the garbage movies that Michael Bay and Roland Emmerich shlog out every few years. Don't mistake Pacific Rim for those franchises and don't for a second try and make Pacific Rim like any of those horrible directors' movies.

text: The trailer looked pretty bloody good. Uprising feels like it's going to be A LOT of fun, and even more action packed than the first. The Jaeger vs Jaeger stuff doesn't bother as much as it seems to for others, due to the fact that the kaiju have been gone for a while, new Jaegers have been built, and there is an obvious internal struggle for power/hierarchy going on. That brings a lot more interesting concepts to the table than just, "Jaegers vs Kaiju" again. I also love how vibrant Uprising is compared to the first movie, and the CG still has time to be touched up, so I'm not worried, and no one else should really be either.  Color me excited for this much more ridiculous, action packed, and colorful story. It's a movie about giant mechs vs other giant mechs vs giant monsters. Go all out.

text: Lots of people saying that the Jagers look like they're moving too fast. You have to remember that most of the battles in Pacific Rim 1 were fought in or completely submerged underwater. A few of the shots from this trailer look like similar movement speed comparable to Striker Eureka in the first movie, when he's taking down the Kaiju in the city (early on, I think).   As far as the movement speed of Saber Athena at 01:43, it kind of makes sense, given that it's supposed to be the fastest and most agile of the group (as per the wiki page, anyway). Still a little too fast though, I get that. I assume Bracer will have the slow, hulking movement speed that we all like.  Honestly though, I think it's a happy medium between Pacific Rim 1 and Transformers speed. Its almost certain that these Jagers will have had some upgrades since the first movie. Let's just hope they aren't moving Armored Core speed in the 3rd movie, haha.

text: I loved the first one and it looks like this will up the action in terms of scale. Other than that it's hard to say because that's all this trailer really showed.  I'll definitely miss Del Toro's direction but most of the new major staff all have some pretty decent stuff on their resumes, but not much really on this level of production. DeKnight did a great job with season 1 of Daredevil, but I think directing a movie like this is a bit more complex given the scope and special effects.  However, I do have to say I'm liking John Boyega from what we've seen. I can't remember the last he was able to actual allowed to speak in his normal voice instead of having to affect an American accent.  Hopefully Ron Perlman will at least have a cameo.

text: Executives from Viacom will travel to China next week to meet with their counterparts at Huahua and to try to reassure them that things will improve in coming months, a source close to Huahua tells Variety. text: I'll remain cautiously optimistic.  While we have little to go off of, I don't really like the emphasis on the weapons over hand-to-hand combat.  The spirit of Kaiju movies is men in rubber suits wrestling each other, and del Toro specified to the artists on the first film that the Jaeger and Kaiju designs should look like a man could wear them as a suit.  Additionally, the way the first film conveyed momentum was perhaps its shining achievement.  It helped suspend disbelief and paced fights out so that every hit landed with the impact of a freight train, after a few seconds of wind up, of course.  Again, there's not a lot to go off of yet, but I have reasons to be skeptical.  I hope it turns out great.

text: Getting way too many flashbacks of transformers with this. Just like transformers the machines had weight to them and actually seemed to interact with objects in a way that made sense in the first movie -- especially in pacific rim, all the actions were slow and meaty because that's how a giant robot would move. Here they just move as if they are made entirely out of packing peanuts and not thousands of tons of metal just like they do in the new transformer movies.   Honestly stuff like that doesn't really bother me especially in a movie where the premise is about giants robots fighting aliens but when you see obvious signs like this that people aren't even caring enough to imitate the style the original was going for it really isn't a good sign for the movie to come. And just wanting to point out that the transformer films that show similar signs got to the level of awful that they are today with their original director still behind them which is even more than i can say for this unfortunately.

text: I am a big fan of Pacific Rim ... I would venture to say one of the biggest in the world (Not trying to be arrogant). But I can not accept what they did with the movie, this is not the Pacific Rim I know, that is: Jaegers where the neural connection was accurate and should be perfect Where there was difficulty locomotion; where most movements were limited; Where the transport should be done with Logistic aid; where each fight should be careful, since each Fight with each Kaiju was Risky, independent of the Kaiju Class or Level, where there was no Fight between Jaegers, since all Jaegers in operation served the Same Purpose, in fact that being the Purpose of the Program Jaeger (The Union of All Nations of the World against the Enemy in Common), where each Jaeger had its characteristic and was not generic, this includes Advantages, Limitations and Personality, the Soundtrack that made sense and made the film even better and each Pilot had a degree of experience, so these drivers could not be teenagers ... THIS FILM WILL NEVER BE PACIFIC RIM, JUST MORE A GENERIC MOVIE WITH ADOLESCENTS, GENERIC JAEGERS, GENERIC KAIJUS, GENERIC CHARACTERS AND GENERIC  PLOT ... This work does not has no relation with the Del Toro Work

text: Looks awesome so far, and I hope the finished product will be even better.  The Jaegers do seem a little bit fast in terms of movement, but from the first scene of the trailer where you can see a Jaeger-vs-Jaeger battle from the perspective of yellow-jacketed Amara (the 'Jaeger hacker' who is seen piloting 'Scrapper', a small Jaeger seen busting out of a barn later in the trailer), the Jaeger's foot movement seem very slow, reminding me of that one scene in Godzilla (2014) where you see Godzilla take a MASSIVE step from the perspective of people in an airport (or some other building) in Hawaii.  Jaegers on rockets seem very cool. I would like Saber Athena's (the red and orange Jeager) movements to be toned down a teensy bit.  Gipsy Avenger's design to me is very cool.  BTW, the Jaegers and Kaiju are DEFINITELY bigger than what you think, Gipsy Avenger will most likely be around 260 ft tall like its predecessor Gipsy Danger.  Titan Redeemer's drill seems a bit overkill which is fine. John Boyega will hopefully be a really good actor in this, since he was great in Star Wars: The Force Awakens.  YES, Mako Mori is in the trailer (look closely, people) and anyways, she's confirmed to be in the film (there's literally going to be a character arc between her and Jake Pentecost).  Kaiju combining is VERY awesome, although I really hope the Kaiju in this film have the same charm, essence, uniqueness and fear factor that the first film had.  I mean, EVERYONE remembers Otachi right? (I hope y'all do).  Hopefully there will be more of them, and that there will still be a Kaiju Category system, it really makes you aware of how powerful these beasts are. Oh, and I hope they are given SICK names, since it gives them a lot of personality (remember in the first film, Raleigh tells his brother that they'll fight a Kaiju called 'Knifehead!' in such a way that you can tell that they love their job?) The first film's Jaegers had lots of moving parts and pistons. They will most likely keep this attention to detail the same in Uprising, and with 5 months till release time, I don't see why they don't give them the same feel the first one gave us. The CGI needs a bit of polishing and fine-tuning, but I'm hopeful. I REALLY want to see those awesome night-time and bad-weather fights that the first movie gave us. In the daytime, it really doesn't give us that pathetic fallacy. The song for the trailer is not 'hip rap stuff that only youngsters like', it's 2Pac's 'Untouchables' slowed down, and he's considered the best rapper EVER.  I am not defending the song choice though (I don't really like it, because the only rap songs I like are Chris Classic's 'I Am A Beast' (used in the Uprising teaser trailer) Eminem's 'Lose Yourself', SOLELY due to the Mom's Spaghetti meme. The new Jaeger designs are really cool in my opinion. So are the Kaiju designs. Hopefully Guillermo Del Toro, even as a producer, will influence the final product in such a way that it FEELS like the original Pacific Rim. I mean, back in 2013, I first watched that film and it became a TIMELESS classic to me, and is still my favourite movie up to now. I want Uprising to continue its legacy. I'm fine with change, just not so much that no one likes it. I am SORT OF worried about Steven S. DeKnight and FOUR OTHER producers, since they might have conflicting visions.  Please stop saying that the new Jaegers look like transformer rip-offs. They aren't.  Of course, they move faster than in the first film. But their movements will only be at the speed of say, Striker Eureka.  I have very high hopes since Pacific Rim is VERY nostalgic for me, I was only 9 when it came out and I got the first film on DVD for my 10th birthday.  I want Uprising to be on its level so I can rewatch it 13 times over without losing interest. I want it to be good since the first film USED TO BE my best friend's favourite film, but now it apparently sucks because of 'plotholes' that I cleared up entirely. Reply if you want to see those debunked.  Also, I  have watched Neon Genesis Evangelion and a few different Mobile Suit Gundam series, and NO! They are nothing like Pacific Rim. Reply if you disagree and I'll point out all the differences. Those who say that Godzilla could squash both these Jaegers and Kaiju, you're also very wrong. Seriously. I am DEFINITELY not against Godzilla though. I love that franchise.  So, that's my thoughts. Agree or disagree? I won't judge.  EDIT: My son asked me if he could write this, he loves this robot film series a lot.
author: Kathryn Hinlo

text: Have to rewatch the first one, but I mainly remember the only thing worth writing home about in the movie were the visual/sound effects, and the performances from Charlie Day and Ron Perlman. The story and all the other characters were pretty forgettable to me. I trust the visuals and audio will be great like before and that John Boyega and Kelly will carry this movie with their acting, but for this to hit home, it has to have more memorable characters, dialogue, and the story needs to be good too. You can have dumb action movies that leave the audience with something afterwards. Starship Troopers, Fury Road, Terminator 2. These are just a few examples, but there are more. I’ll see this film and will wish it the best of luck.

text: The trailer looks promising and I really hope it's good, but part of it doesn't feel like the first one. It doesn't have the same rainy, cloudy atmosphere that made the action sequences in the first one so epic, and the Jaegers are a little too swift and weightless and less mechanical than they should be. In that shot where Gipsy is fighting that enemy Jaeger in a city, there's no sense of scale and their lack of weight makes them feel human-sized. Also, I found it a little off-putting that the trailer barely focused on the kaiju themselves, but rather the Jaegers. Did they forget why the Jaegers were created in the first place??? And the kaiju they showed all seemed to be from the same set piece, which is kind of disheartening because I loved the variety of locations and Jaegers from the fight scenes in the original. Hopefully they haven't shown too much in this trailer because I really want to see some more variety in the fight sequences than just "giant robot vs giant monster in generic city full of skyscrapers".

text: I LOVE the first one, L O V E it! So when I see the cockpit of these new Jaegers don't have any of the practical machinery (what the pilots were locked into) and is substituted with only neon holographic images instead and rubber hoses, I have to ask just how much work really went into this?   I want it to be good, I really really do. I never thought we would even get a second one! But when all the main characters are replaced, we get a cliched "son of former character" lead, all the pilots look like teenagers and battle scenes that look weightless, I start to worry. I had the same feelings with Suicide Squad and Batman v Superman trailers. I pray I'm wrong on this one.

text: I can never tell when people are gonna hate on a movie for it's "bad CGI." It's totally random. And, as far as I can tell, never has anything to do with the quality of the CGI. I'm gonna go out on a limb and say it has more to do with people being bitter because it has replaced practical effects. The only consistent standard I've heard is that it's bad CGI "If I can tell it's CGI." That's like saying blue paint is bad if you can tell it's blue. You clearly just don't like CGI. Guess what? Some of us do. If you want puppets, go watch "Gremlins." Great movie, but I digress.  Pacific Rim Uprising looks awesome! I love the first one, and I can't wait to see how this one turns out!

text: I don't know if I am the only one feeling this but, does anyone think this new jaegers doesn't look as powerful as the old ones in Pacific Rim 1?  These jaegers shown in the trailer are like toys with armors in light colors (instead of steel), flashy lightsaber or electrified lash. They seems more agile in the new trailer but they also look thin and weak. Just think about Gipsy Danger and Cherno Alpha in Pacific Rim 1, just recall the sense of power they've shown on the big screen. You can feel the power by limited movement speed, the steel color, and the renders: you can even feel the smell of rust in the movie theater. Now look at these new babies, uh. Again they look like toys and the combats are more like playing video games rather than beating a monster to death and fighting for the survival of mankind.

text: In all honesty, I am super hyped for this.   [warning. Opinion incoming. Feminists, SJWs, and nerds look away now]  This movie looks like it will be a major letdown. The darker, more serious tone of the first one seemed more realistic. That, and the fact that the situation looked realistic and felt like it could happen made it amazing. They ended on a positive note that should have been the end of the story.   But of course... Hollywood does not know how to let things die.  This one looks more for sole purpose of a cash grab while keying in on an epic story. This sequel was not asked for, although if it is good, it will be appreciated. This looks like your every day action film where the big guy saves the world and gets the girl. The first one was not so different from that narrative, but it actually brought some new stuff to the table from old and classic ideas. This is basically a parody. If it is good, I will be thankful. If it is not, I will be incredibly disappointed.

text: It could be a fun movie, but it doesn't look anywhere near as good as the original. Two aspects of this film make it inferior so far. 1. The weight of the Jeagers. In the original, they moved like giant robots. Even when they ran, they had a sense of weight to them. This made fights much more interesting and entertaining, since the pilots were controlling a heavy tank, while the Kaiju could easily maneuver around. Here, they pretty much look like giant, armored people, with very little sense of weight. For a comparison, the Megazord from the new Power Rangers movie had weight. And 2. The sense of scale. The original film was shot in such a way that it made the Jeagers feel giant, when compared to say a building or even the people. They felt large and dangerous to use. Here, there's none of that.   Now, don't get me wrong, I really want this to be good. But what I've seen hasn't instill confidence.

Like I see what they did with the new Gipsy Danger having a blade on its right arm like Gypsy danger had the sword, but I honestly prefer the less scifi more realistic jaegers. text: Here's the thing: I liked the first pacific rim because although it was about Kaijus and jagers it was gritty, less Transformer/power rangery, more dystopian and less "young adults are the only ones who can save the world type thing. It was a healthy mix but this seems way left field, it is definitely the direct successor to the original but it has become "colourful" with the maze runner, hunger games, new power rangers, divergent type focus on "young adults who must save the world, only they can".... at least thats the feel it gives off these early stages. It now has that transformers and power rangers feel to it and thats not a good thing imo but we will see. these are initial thoughts anyways.   I lov John Boyega but if this movie is campy, even his young charisma wont save a typical young kids are the only ones who can save the world with giant robots type cliche storyline. Again, the first one wasnt void of this, it was a healthy balance imo

text: I'm a huge fan on the first movie, I've even used GipsyDanger as my online moniker for a while, and I have to say I am pretty bummed out by this trailer. I think it sucks to see people rationalize the negative comments as being inconsequential because it's a "Dumb big robot movie, and it doesn't need to be anything more". I think thematically the first Pacific Rim was interesting in both its narrative as well as its distinctive art style. The acting was well done, and you felt like the world was brought to life through the efforts of Del Toro. Even through small details like the labored movements of the Jaegers which gave a sense of scale as to how large they are, and the properties of physics that would not allow them to move as quickly as they are in the above trailer. Just throwing in my two cents as an avid fan, I hope I'm wrong and this film is just as good as the first.

text: The thing I want is a movie or series about Cherno Alpha. Also, what moron gave a robot a spiky rocket fist? Have they done no research about the Pacific Rim lore at all?  Also, is that girl a teenager or just a short woman? Cause from the look of it, most of those candidates appear to be kids... which is extremely stupid as during the initiation of the neural link you need to have pretty strong hold over your emotions. Teens are also emotional and likely to lose their head.   If the candidates were 25+ I would not have any issues with this, but from what I could see they were not. Sure, if *all* the older pilots had been killed this could be understandable, but generally, you *don't* put a 15 year old kid at the front in a warzone. Especially if that kid is supposedly a genius that might have created the only *single pilot neural link* in the whole world.   You would keep her out of danger and make her try to recreate it as this would mean that the restriction of candidates would disappear and you would be able to recruit many more thousands of people able to pilot their own jaegers...   I was initially excited for this movie, but after I calmed down and truly *saw* the trailer for what it was, I kind of lost faith in this movie. They are pulling off way too many unbelievable things (even for Pacific Rim) that I honestly do feel a bit let down. The having "young cadets" rather than the old crew is pretty much to try to appeal to younger audience in the US whilst the rest of the world enjoyed the older crew of the first movie just fine.  They did this for financial gain, not because they story would be more interesting that way. And after the hundreds of "teen saves the world" movies we have been getting the past decade I am personally sick and tired of that trope. : /
